<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-660-387  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 660 387.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 26 1990 n618 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DOD budget cuts increase electronics share. (Department ofDefense) (part of a special section comprising ElectronicEngineering Times' annual report on the military segment of theelectronics market)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The impact of inevitable cuts in defense spending on the militaryelectronics market may be mitigated by a shift toward 'smarter'weapons technologies supported by advanced electronics and by thegrowing market for retrofits and upgrades.andP;  The ElectronicIndustries Association (EIA) predicts that the electronicscomponent of the research, development, test and evaluation(RDTandamp;E) will continue to gain percentage, and could account fornearly half the total by the year 2000, although even at thatlevel the actual dollar amount will represent a significantdecline for the decade, albeit at a pace that will allow theindustry time to adjust.andP;  Even the current move toward usingcommercially available products in place of customized militaryproducts, while reducing business for military specialists, offersmore business to the market as a whole.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisMilitaryElectronic IndustryBudgetingGovernment Funding.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Tight budgets to produce 'smarter' weapons via electronics.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>